Five truths concerning terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or approximately 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, never had so many Americans been this concerned about terrorism, even though their numbers are still far below the 46% recorded right after the 9/11 attacks in 2001.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were most prominently felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not outright incendiary), has undoubtedly benefited from it.
Some politicians authorize themselves to speak of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But candidates in the presidential election, as well as some media outlets, adherents to the old maxim "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – as others do – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a sort of theater.
The terrorists are more worried about retaining attention and dominating political news than about the number of their victims in and of themselves.
The Islamic State (IS) pays great attention to its staging.
The barbaric beheadings posted on social networks are intended to destabilize and scandalize – and consequently to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making big headlines with each terrorist action is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the greatest threat facing the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills much less than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a genuine threat – neither major nor minor.
The English translation of the given French sentence is: "We have more chance of being struck by lightning than of being killed by a terrorist."
The probability that an American citizen will be assassinated by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
The Americans have a higher risk of dying in their bathtub (one in 950,000), from an accident involving household equipment (one in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (one in 2 million), or in the crash of a commercial airplane (one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while texting or talking on their phones while driving.
It is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by dissatisfied employees or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist flare-up.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed several heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Armed Red Fraction, which emerged from the "autonomous" left, hijacked aircraft outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are a old political phenomenon cloaked in a religious garment.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identities have been destroyed by globalization, who seek meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of the EI limits its appeal.
His sectarian attacks already prevent him from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
The EI will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorism that preceded it has been defeated.
Terrorism is like jiujitsu.
The weakest of the two adversaries uses the strength of the strongest to defeat them.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke citizens of a state enough to push them into fruitless actions, they can hope to gain an advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda managed to lure the Americans into Afghanistan.
The EI was born from the ruins of the Iraq invasion led by the United States, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, you need smart power.
A smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the influence power (soft power) of attraction and persuasion.
The influence and power are also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and to prevent the unreceptive from recruiting others.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and to the way in which the actions of the United States are commented on social networks is just as important and necessary as precision aerial strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
The reason why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential election candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist question is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important data point in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap laid by the terrorists.
Let's not fill the theater where actions carried out by thugs and hoodlums unfold.
If we leave them the big stage of our public speech, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and expose our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
